[
    {
        "content": "<p><a href=\"https://rust-for-linux.com/the-safe-pinned-initialization-problem\">The alternative of allocating it on the heap, i.e. returning a Pin&lt;Box&lt;ListHead&gt;&gt; also does not work, since this list should be part of a bigger struct.</a>.  Since the list is part of a bigger struct,  but why Pin&lt;Box&lt;ListHeAD&gt;&gt; does not work?</p>",
        "id": 416720375,
        "sender_full_name": "Baul (Jianguo Bao)",
        "timestamp": 1705648182
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Because if you create a <code>Pin&lt;Box&lt;ListHead&gt;&gt;</code>, then you have only the list heads, but no data associated to them. In C you would normally do this:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"C\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"k\">struct</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nc\">foo</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">struct</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nc\">list_head</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">head</span><span class=\"p\">;</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"kt\">int</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">value</span><span class=\"p\">;</span>\n<span class=\"p\">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>And you need to do the same in Rust. <code>Pin&lt;Box&lt;ListHead&gt;&gt;</code> is functionally the same as:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"C\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"k\">struct</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nc\">foo</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">struct</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nc\">list_head</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">head</span><span class=\"p\">;</span>\n<span class=\"p\">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Which is pretty much useless.</p>",
        "id": 416722012,
        "sender_full_name": "Benno Lossin",
        "timestamp": 1705649094
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh, Thanks</p>",
